<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF Research Continues Through the Holidays</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Shobana Daniell
		
		<span class="date">Dec. 22, 2005</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
			
			
			
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.research.ucf.edu">Office of Research and Commercialization</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=0024004105c1b71a90107dcb09eb80074b6"></a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>While the campus may look empty with no students dashing to classes, no shuttle buses picking up riders and no faculty rushing to their offices, many dedicated UCF researchers continue to work in their laboratories during the holiday break. </p><p>Sidhartha Pandey, a doctoral student in the <place /><placetype />College</placetype /> of <placename />Optics</placename /></place /> and Photonics, said he wont be going home for the holidays because I wouldnt get any studying or research done at home in <city /><place />Seattle</place /></city />. This is his first semester at UCF, and he wants to keep up with assignments because my project is part of a bigger research program and needs to be on schedule. </p><p>Anyone who walks through the Biological Sciences building might think the semester has not ended yet. Groups of students walk through the hallways to get to their labs and catch up on important experiments that require long stretches of attention. That is often a luxury when classes are in session. </p><p>The spring semester will begin Jan. 9. Administrative offices are closed from Dec. 23 through Dec. 26 and again from Dec. 30 through Jan. 2. </p><p>During the break, it is not unusual to see the Burnett College of Biomedical Sciences scientists rushing in even at <time hour="0" minute="0" />midnight</time /> to check on their experiments. Dean Pappachan Kolattakudy said most of the professors and many students remain on a regular schedule. </p><p>Experiments and research in the biomedical sciences are ongoing and cannot be interrupted, he said. </p><p>As UCF hires more professors and and generates more research funding, the university is home to more research projects that keep faculty and students busy during breaks. In 2004-05, UCF topped the $100 million milestone in research funding for the first time. </p><p>Two busy post-doctoral scientists are working in the Organic Research Lab at the Chemistry Department. Navneet Kaur barely had time to explain that she and her colleague, Bo Zhou, will be working through the break. </p><p>Most of the time, depending on the research experiment, I need to be here to see how the reactions are going on in the cell-culture studies, Kaur said. </p><p>Professor Otto Phanstiel, who heads that lab, explained that his group is researching drug delivery technology. Cancer cells require polyamine cells to grow, and Phansteils group is figuring out ways to attach drugs to those cells and penetrate and kill the cancer cells selectively. </p><p>Because that important work requires constant experiments and monitoring, Phanstiel and his staff will come to work even when the campus is officially closed. </p><p>A couple of undergraduate research assistants in Phansteils laboratory will stay during the holidays to help with the assignments, which include progress reports that have to be sent to the biotech companies underwriting some of the research. </p><p>In the <place /><placetype />College</placetype /> of <placename />Business Administration</placename /></place />, Neeraj Parolia, a third-year doctoral student in Management Information Systems, was trying to maximize his time in the computer lab before it closed for the holidays. </p><p>This is the time when I catch up on the extra reading and research for my dissertation work, he said. School resources are very important; home Internet work is not enough. </p><p>He added that most doctoral students he knows in other UCF departments work more during the break -- way beyond the normal schedule. The extra work and reading generally result in getting some new ideas that can be used in ongoing research. </p>
		
	
	<p id="back"><a href="index?page=news">&lt; Back to the Newsroom</a></p>

